@page "/getting-started"
<PageTitle>Getting started — Settex</PageTitle>

<h1>Getting started</h1>
<p class="lead">
    Settex turns a single <code>.settex</code> source file into <code>appsettings.json</code> and one
    file per environment. There are two ways to compile: automatically during an MSBuild build, or
    manually with the CLI.
</p>

<h2 id="install-msbuild">Option A — MSBuild integration (recommended)</h2>
<p>Add the <code>Settex.Build</code> package to your project:</p>
<CodeBlock Lang="bash" Code="dotnet add package Settex.Build" />
<p>
    Create a <code>appsettings.settex</code> file in your project root. It is discovered and compiled
    automatically on every build — the generated JSON stays in sync with your source.
</p>

<h2 id="install-cli">Option B — CLI tool</h2>
<p>Install the compiler as a global .NET tool:</p>
<CodeBlock Lang="bash" Code="dotnet tool install --global Settex.Cli" />
<p>Then compile a file whenever you need to:</p>
<CodeBlock Lang="bash" Code="@("settex build appsettings.settex\nsettex build config.settex -o ./output")" />

<h2 id="first-file">Your first file</h2>
<p>Create <code>appsettings.settex</code>:</p>
<CodeBlock Title="appsettings.settex" Code="@FirstFile" />

<p>Compile it, and Settex generates three files:</p>
<ul>
    <li><code>appsettings.json</code> — the base settings</li>
    <li><code>appsettings.Development.json</code> — base merged with the Development overlay</li>
    <li><code>appsettings.Production.json</code> — base merged with the Production overlay</li>
</ul>

<CodeBlock Title="appsettings.Development.json" Lang="json" Code="@GeneratedDev" />

<div class="callout callout-note">
    An <code>env</code> block takes a <strong>quoted</strong> name and wraps its overrides in an inner
    <code>settings { … }</code> block: <code>env "Development" { settings { … } }</code>. This is the one
    piece of syntax that trips people up — the base <code>settings</code> block is written at the top level,
    the environment ones are nested inside <code>env</code>.
</div>

